THIS PACKAGE WAS LEAKING WHEN TAKEN OUT OF THE FREIGHT CONTAINER DURING THE INBOUND SORT OPERATION.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELINGS ON THE BOX TO LEAD FEDEX TO BELIEVE THAT THIS WAS A DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT.  NO DANGEROUS GOODS PAPERWORK WAS PROVIDED TO FEDERAL EXPRESS.  SINCE THIS WAS OBVIOUSLY A PERFUME/COLOGNE TYPE OF SPILL, THE SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST NOTIFIED ME ABOUT THIS POSSIBLE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT.  WHEN THE SPILL SPECIALIST INSPECTED THE INNER CONTENTS, HE FOUND 4 15 ML. BOTTLES OF PERFUME THAT HAD NOT SPILLED OR LEAKED.  I NOTIFIED THE FAA ABOUT THIS HIDDEN SHIPMENT.  THIS PACKAGE WAS HELD, PENDING THE INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.

Paschall Truck Lines driver had stopped at a truck stop.  Whenever driver returned to the tractor he discovered that the had product leaking from the rear of his trailer.  Driver notified PTL and then the truck stop.  The truck stop called the fire department, which isolated and contained the area until Environmental Management Inc (EMI) could get a sub-contractor out to clean the spill.  The spill which came from the punctured 55 gallon drum was neutralized and cleaned up.  The waste was placed into an overpack drum and was accepted by the consignee this morning along with the rest of the load.

WE WERE TRAVELING EAST IN THE MIDDLE LANE OF ROUTE 38.  OUR UNIT HAD STOPPED FOR A TRAFFIC LIGHT AND AS WE BEGAN TO PROCEED FORWARD A WASH-OUT CAP CAME OFF.  APPROXIMATELY 25-30 GALLONS OF SULFURIC ACID WAS RELEASED ONTO THE ROADWAY.  OUR DRIVER IMMEDIATELY STOPPED, PUT ON HIS FLASHERS AND PLACED HIS REFLECTIVE WARNING TRIANGLES BEHIND HIS TRAILER.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE NJ DEP HANDLED THE DECONTAMINATION OF THE SPILL.  THE ACID WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA-ASH AND LARGE QUANTITIES OF WATER.  NO ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE OR WASTE RESULTED FROM THE SPILL.  THE TANK-TRAILER HAD BEEN WASHED INTERNALLY AT A COMMERCIAL TANK WAS FACILITY PRIOR TO THE PICK-UP. ONE OF THE WASH-OUT CAPS HAD BEEN CROSS-THREADED.  APPARENTLY THE WASH-OUT ATTENDANT HAD RE-ATTACHED THE CAP IMPROPERLY.  THE THREADS ON THE NOZZLE FOR THE WASH-OUT CAP WERE GOUGED.  THE NOZZLE HAD TO BE REPLACED WITH A BLANK FLANGE BEFORE THE TRAILER COULD BE MOVED FROM THE SPILL SITE.

WHEN THE PALLET OF CORROSIVE LIQUID BOXES ARRIVED AT OUR FEDEX RAMP FACILITY, ONE OF THE BOXES WAS FOUND TO HAVE BEEN DAMAGED, MOST LIKELY BY A FORKLIFT TYPE OF VEHICLE.  I RECEIVED A CALL ABOUT THIS SPILL AND FOUND THAT THIS BOX WAS THE ONLY ONE OUT OF ABOUT TWENTY BOXES THAT LEAKED.  THE SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST FOLLOWED PROPER FEDEX CLEANUP PROCEDURES AND THE SHIPMENT WAS PICKED UP BY THE CONSIGNEE.

column168: OUR DRIVER PICKED UP A LOADED VAN AT SAFETY KLEEN IN PECATONICA. HE INSPECTED THE TRAILER AND LEFT WITH THE LOAD. HE STOPPED AT A TRUCK STOP IN LITTLE ROCK, AR. WHEN HE NOTICED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE CORNER OF TRAILER. HE CONTAINED THE LEAK WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND CALLED 3E ENVIRONMENTAL TO OVERPACK AND DECON TRAILER. 3E DISCOVERED A LID WAS LOOSE ON ONE OF THE DRUMS. THEY ESTIMATED LOSS OF APPROXIMATELY 1 QUART OF ACETONE. TRAILER WAS EMPTIED INTO A SECOND TRAILER WHERE LEAKER WAS OVERPACKED, TRAILER WAS DECONED AND THEN RELOADED.

OUR DRIVER WAS TOLD WHEN BEING LOADED THAT THERE WAS AN OLDER DRUM BUT IT WAS NOT LEAKING. ENROUTE IN LOUISIANA, A WOMEN IN A CAR POINTED TO OUR DRIVER AND AT THE TRAILER. OUR DRIVER PULLED OVER ON BERM AND LOOKED AROUND UNIT, WHEN HE FOUND AN OIL STAIN AND A FEW DROPS ON RIGHT CORNER OF TRAILER AND ICE BUMPER. DRIVER TOOK OUT SPILL KIT AND WIPED UP. BUMPER AND OIL STAIN. DRIVER THEN OPENED TRAILER DOOR AND NOTICED OIL ON FLOOR OF SPILL PAN. THE SPILL PAN WAS CONTAINING THE OIL EXCEPT IN THE CORNER WHERE GASKET PRESSURE WAS LEAST. DRIVER PUT AN ABSORBENT BOOM AND OIL DRI TO CONTAIN LEAK. LEAK WAS STOPPED. LOAD WAS TAKEN TO DEER PARK, TX WHERE THE INSIDE SPILL PAN WAS CLEANED UP AND ALSO DECONTAMINATED.

column168: TEN DRUMS ON THIS SHIPMENT WERE HEADLOADED INTO JACKSON, MS ON THE FLOOR. TWO SKIDS OF DRUMS WERE LOADED BEHIND THE SHIPMENT. DURING THE ROUTINE INSPECTION AT 0350 OF KZ107/07 MAY 99 WHICH EN ROUTE TO SAN FRANCISCO FROM NEW YORK (JFK), WE FOUND LEAKING OF THE ABOVE DANGEROUS GOODS AT THE BOTTOM OF PALLET PMP1726KZ. THE PALLET WAS OFFLOADED FROM THE FLIGHT AND STAGED AT AN OPEN RAMP AREA 0445. CONTACTED THE AIRPORT EMERGENCY AT 6-2323 AT 0600. THE HAZ MAT SPECIALIST ARRIVED AT 0730 AND INSPECTION ALL THE DANGEROUS GOODS DOCUMENTATION AND THE BUILD-UP CONDITION OF THE PALLET. SUBSEQUENTLY, UNDER THE DIRECTION OF THE  WAREHOUSE. AT 1100, THE DAMAGED BOX WAS REMOVED BY MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (CHEMTREC). AT 1500, ALL CONTAMINATED PACKAGINGS WERE SEGREGATED AND REMOVED FROM OTHER CARGO LOADED ON THE SAME PALLET. FIRE DEPARTMENT, THE HAZ MAT SPECIALIST AND AIRPORT OPERATION PERSONNEL WERE PRESENT AT THE SCENE ALL THE TIME UNTIL THE TASK WAS COMPLETED BY MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES.

column168: THE TRUCK WAS LOADED IN FREEPORT, TX AT ROCHE VITAMINS. THE DRIVER LEFT THE CUSTOMER WITHOUT DOUBLE CHECKING HIS DOME LIDS. HE GOT APPROXIMATELY 2 MILES DOWN THE ROAD BEFORE HE NOTICED THE LIQUID COMING OUT OF THE DOME. HE IMMEDIATELY STOPPED AND SECURED THE DOME LID, AND WIPED UP WHAT MATERIAL HE SAW. HE THEN CALLED THE INCIDENT INTO OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE COORDINATOR. IT WAS THEN DETERMINED THAT IT WAS NOT A REPORTABLE QUANTITY, AND THE DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO BRING THE LOAD INTO THE AVALON TERMINAL. THE NEXT MORNING THE GENERATOR WAS NOTIFIED WHO DETERMINED THE MATERIAL WAS A NON-HAZARDOUS BIODEGRADABLE SUBSTANCE. THE GENERATOR'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS SENT TO DOW-CORNINGS PARKING LOT (WHICH IS WHERE THE DRIVER STOPPED) AND CLEANED THE RED SUBSTANCE WITH A PEROXIDE SOLUTION. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE AMOUNT ON THE ROAD WOULD DISSIPATE WITH THE SUNLIGHT. THE DRIVER HAS BEEN WRITTEN UP FOR THE INCIDENT, AND OF COARSE HAS BEEN RE-REVIEWED ON OUR S.O.P. FOR LOADING AND SECURING LOADS. WE HAVE ALSO HAD OUR QUARTERLY SAFETY MEETING SINCE THIS INCIDENT AND HAVE REVIEWED AND STRESSED TO ALL OF OUR EMPLOYEES THE NECESSITY OF FOLLOWING PROPER PROCEDURE IN SECURING ALL LOADS !
WHILE FREIGHT WAS BEING UNLOADED IT WAS NOTICED THAT IT WAS LEAKING AROUND THE SEAM. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED PROPERLY AND THE DAMAGED FREIGHT WAS PUT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND SENT ONTO DESTINATION.

column168: CPDX 84490 WAS OBSERVED IN YARD TO BE VENTING FROM SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  THE VENTING WAS OCCURRING ABOUT EVERY 45 MINUTES.  THE CAR WAS PLACED ON THE DESIGNATED ISOLATION TRACK AND COOLED WITH WATER SPRAY, THE NEW ORLEANS FD ASSISTED WITH THIS ENDEAVOR.  THE PRESSURE TAKEN ON THE CAR JUST AFTER A VENTING PERIOD WAS 275 PSIG.  THE CAR WAS BELIEVED TO BE OVERLOADED.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE THROUGH THE SHIPPER TO OFF LOAD A TRUCK TANKER OF PRODUCT.  AN ESTIMATED 2300 GALLONS WERE OFF LOADED.  THE CAR WAS MONITORED AFTER REMOVING THE PRODUCT AND THE PRESSURE STABILIZED WITH NO FURTHER VENTING.

WHILE THE YARD CREW WAS MAKING A SWITCH MOVE THEY NOTICE TANK CAR TCDX 13198 WITH A SLOSH LEAK.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.  SWS ENV. RESPONDED, CLEAN OFF THE RAIL CAR AND REPOSITIONED AND SECURED THE GASKET ON THE LIQUID FILL HOLE.  AFTER THE CAR WAS CHECKED FOR LEAKS IT WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE UNTO DESTINATION.

WHEN THE YARD CREW WAS MAKING A SWITCH ON RAIL TANK CAR GATX 61457. THEY NOTICE A VAPOR RELEASE FROM THE TOP.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.  CLEAN HARBORS RESPONDED AND REPLACED A BLOWN RUPTURE DISK.

WHILE YARD CREW WAS MAKING A SWITCH MOVE THEY FOUND RAIL TANK CAR GATX 61330 WITH A SLOSH LEAK FROM THE TOP.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED. LOCAL AUTHORITIES AND STATE PATROL WAS NOTIFIED.  MR. BILL GLEASON WITH THE CSX TRANSPORTATION HAZMAT DEPT RESPONDED AND REPLACED A BLOWN RUPTURE DISK.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO CONTINUE UNTO DESTINATION.

1138HR- OP CTR REPORTED STRONG ODOR COMING FROM 1 OF 2 TANK CARS IN RO2 TRACK IN WAYCROSS, GA.  TJRX 30018 & CELX 8310, LDS METHYL ACRYLATE.  1159 HRS SHIPPER NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  HAZMAT SENIOR MGR EGC RESPONDED.  DETERMINED ODORS COMING FROM CELX 8310. INSPECTION REVEALED 1) 1 MANWAY BOLT HANGING DOWN, 2) 1 MANWAY BOLT LESS THAN HAND TIGHT, 3) 5 OF REMAINING 8 BOLTS WERE LESS WRENCH TIGHT, EGC CHECKED MANWAY GASKET; IT WAS OK, SECURED MANWAY BOLTS WRENCH TIGHT.  INSPECTED PLUGS ON AIR LINE & LIQUID VALVE.  OBSERVED SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID BYPASS ON THE LIQUID VALVE. REWRAPPED BOTH PLUGS WITH TEFLON TAPE & INSTALLED THEM WRENCH TIGHT.  CHECKED TJRX 30018, EVERYTHING WAS SECURE.  COULD NO LONGER DETECT ANY ODORS & RELEASED CAR.

1402HRS- PCC REPORTS A LEAKING TANK CAR IN TAMPA. THE TRAINMASTER REPORTED A CARMAN OBSERVED GATX 14013.  LD CORROSIVE LIQ NOS TO SLOSH PRODUCT FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED ON TRACK 29.  1422HRS - SHIPPER NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  MS SHIRLEY MCCANN, PBI 800-821-7925 CALLED OK'D CSXT TO CALL SWS, AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO RESPOND TO MAKE REPAIRS, SWS CHECKED SECUREMENT BOLTS ON 8 INCH FILL HOLE COVER.  THE 2 INCH LIQUID LINE & THE 2 INCH AIR LINE 8 BOLTS ON PHLANGE ON LIQUID LINE WERE NOT WRENCH TIGHT.  THEY SECURED BOLTS & HAD A YARD ENGINE MOVE CAR. WHEN THE CAR WAS COUPLED PRODUCT SPLASHED FROM THE TOP.  SWS IDENTIFIED SPLASH CAME FROM THE 2 IN AIR LINE.  SWS DETERMINED THERE WAS NO RUPTURE DISK IN THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY, SWS  INSTALLED A 100# DISK TO MOVE THE CAR A SHORT DISTANCE TO THE CONSIGNEE.  A YARD ENGINE COUPLED INTO CAR & THERE WAS NO PRODUCT LEAKAGE.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED.

ON MAY 12, 1999, FACILITY PERSONNEL WERE DISCONNECTING A TRANSFER HOSE FROM A RAILCAR (ACFX79302) WHEN APPROXIMATELY 75 GALLON OF FUEL WAS RELEASED FROM THE RAILCAR. ALL OF THE FUEL DRAINED INTO THE CONCRETE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AT THE FUELS FACILITY. THE SPILL OCCURRED AT 21:45, FOAM WAS APPLIED IMMEDIATELY TO REDUCE VAPORS, ALL FREE LIQUID WAS CLEAN-UP AT 22:45. VERBAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO THE APPROPRIATE AGENCIES. THE ENTIRE RELEASE COVERED AN APPROXIMATE 320 SQUARE FOOT AREA. EMISSION CALCULATIONS FROM THE RELEASED VAPORS ARE ATTACHED (9.4 LBS RELEASED TO ATMOSPHERE). THE WASTE CODES ASSOCIATED WITH THE MATERIAL ARE ALSO ATTACHED. THE AREA WAS IMMEDIATELY SECURED AND FUEL WAS CLEANED-UP USING ABSORBENT PADS. ALL MATERIALS USED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL WERE PLACED INTO DRUMS AND WILL BE SENT OFF-SITE FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. THE WASTE DERIVED FUEL WAS NOT KNOWN TO CONTAIN ANY EXTREMELY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCES. THE EMPLOYEE EXPERIENCED SOME MINOR IRRITATION UNTIL THE DECONTAMINATION PROCESS WAS COMPLETE. NO OTHER INJURIES WERE INCURRED AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT. NO ACTUAL OR POTENTIAL HAZARDS TO HUMAN HEALTH AND THE ENVIRONMENT REMAIN AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT. NO EVACUATION WAS REQUIRED. NO CONTAMINATION OF ANY WATER BODY OCCURRED.

UA FLIGHT 934 DEPARTED LAX FOR LONDON ON MAY 24, 1999 @1811. THE FLIGHT WAS SCHEDULED TO GO DIRECTLY TO LHR BUT WAS DIVERTED TO CHICAGO FOR RELOADING OF DANGEROUS GOODS. AN ERROR WAS MADE AT LAX WHEN THE AIRCRAFT WAS LOADED. TWO PALLETS WITH 48LBS EACH OF LABELED DANGEROUS GOODS WERE BOARDED IN THE SAME COMPARTMENT OF THE AIRCRAFT. AT APPROXIMATELY 1900 THIS ERROR WAS NOTICED AND THE DECISION WAS MADE TO LAND AT CHICAGO AND RELOAD THE PALLETS IN SEPARATE COMPARTMENTS. A FULL INVESTIGATION WAS CONDUCTED. ALL PARTIES INVOLVED WILL BE RETRAINED WITH EMPHASIS ON PROPER COMMUNICATION WITH THE CONTROL CENTER. ALL PARTIES WILL BE COUNSELED/DISCIPLINED AS APPROPRIATE.

column168: THE GRANT WESTERN CHEMICAL COMPANY (GWCC) DRIVER CAME TO A SUDDEN STOP AFTER BEING CUT OFF. TWO BOTTLES OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID CAME OUT OF THE PLASTIC BOX ("CRATE") AND THE LIDS FAILED, CAUSING 2 GALLONS OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID TO SPILL IN THE VEHICLE. THE DRIVER HAD PICKED UP THE INCORRECT MATERIAL AT HASA TO BRING BACK TO GWSS- ARLETA. BEFORE THE DRIVER RETURNED TO GWCC, THE SPILL OCCURED. GWCC DOES NOT CARRY THE HYDROCHLORIC ACID AND HAD TO RELY ON HASA, INC. TO PROVIDE PACKAGING INFORMATION LISTED IN #30-40 OF THIS FORM. THE CASES OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID WORE PACKAGED IN AN OPEN-TOP CRATE UNDER DOT-E6614. THE CAUSE OF THE SPILL WAS THE LIDS BREAKING OR POPPING OFF THE PLASTIC BOTTLES WHEN THE DRIVER CAME TO QUICK STOP, RELEASING WITH THE TRUCK COMING TO A QUICK STOP ARE THE CAUSES OF THE RELEASE. NO RECOMMENDATIONS ABOUT PACKAGING CAN BE MADE BY GWCC SINCE WE DO NOT HANDLE THIS PACKAGING REGULARLY. TO PREVENT OCCURRENCES, THE DRIVER WAS RETRAINED ON PICKING UP PRODUCTS (TO PREVENT PICKING UP THE INCORRECT PRODUCTS). ALSO, HE WAS RETRAINED ON LOAD SECUREMENT.

THE WASTE CORROSIVE LIQUID WAS PUMPED INTO THE TANKER ON TUESDAY AFTERNOON, 5-11-99.  THE TANKER WAS BROUGHT TO THE AETS-CONTROLLED WASTE DIVISION SITE TO BE PARKED UNTIL WEDNESDAY MORNING, 5-12-99, WHEN A DIFFERENT DRIVER WILL TRANSPORT THE WASTE TO THE DESTINATION FACILITY.  WHEN THE DRIVER ARRIVED AT AETS TO HOOK UP THE TANKER ON 5-12-99 AT 3:15AM.  HE DISCOVERED THE TANKER LEAKING.  THE DRIVER ACTIVATED THE EMERGENCY SHUT-OFF VALVE AND CONTACTED AETS AND MIDWEST TRANSPORT MANAGEMENT. THE AETS AND MIDWEST TRANSPORT PERSONNEL ARRIVE ON-SITE AT APPROXIMATELY 4:00AM.  THE EMERGENCY SHUT-OFF VALVE DIDN'T WORK SO THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO DRAW A VACUUM ON THE TANKER TO STOP THE SPILL.  BEFORE THE VACUUM COULD BE DRAWN, THE ENTIRE CONTENTS 1,500 GALLONS, HAD BEEN RELEASED.  APPROXIMATELY 500 GALLONS WAS CAPTURED IN SECONDARY CONTAINMENT, AND THE REMAINDER WASHED DOWN A DITCH AND INTO A RETENTION POND.  DURING THE RELEASE IT WAS RAINING.  THE RAIN STOPPED AT APPROXIMATELY THE SAME TIME THE RELEASE STOPPED.  ALL MATERIAL WITHIN THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AND THE DOCKETS IN THE DITCH WERE PUMPED INTO 55 GALLON POLY DRUMS. APPROXIMATELY SIX INCHES OF SOIL WAS EXCAVATED FROM THE DRAINAGE DITCH AND REPLACED WITH ROCK.  THE MATERIAL WAS FOUND TO HAVE CORRODED THROUGH THE VALVES ON THE TANKER.  THE MATERIAL COLLECTED IS IN STORAGE AT AETS.  SAMPLES WERE COLLECTED FROM SIX OF THE CONTAINERS AND SHIPPED TO A LABORATORY TO BE ANALYZED FOR PERCENT ACIDITY AND ANIONS.
EQUIPMENT FAILURE WAS THE CAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT.  PUMP DID NOT SHUT OFF COMPLETELY.

column168: CONSIGNEE'S PERSONNEL WAS DRUMMING OFF PRODUCT FROM CARGO TANK. DRIVER WAS OPERATING PUMP.  UNLOADER DROPPED DRUMMING NOZZLE AND IT CRACKED AND STARTED TO LEAK.  DRIVER SHUT OFF PUMP AND SPREAD OIL DRY ON PRODUCT AND CONSIGNEE'S PERSONNEL FINISHED CLEANING UP SPILL. UNLOADER HAD CUT ON LEG WHEN THE NOZZLE SLIPPED OUT OF HIS HAND.  HE WAS SENT TO THE HOSPITAL TO RECEIVE TREATMENT ON LEG.  HE WAS THEN RELEASED.

AFTER CARGO TANK WENT EMPTY, DRIVER UNHOOKED TRANSFER HOSE AND HAD CONSIGNEE'S UNLOADING PERSONNEL HOLD ONE END WHILE HE WALKED THE HOSE TO DRAIN INTO THE TRANSFER PUMP TO CLEAR AND EMPTY LINES INTO CONSIGNEE'S STORAGE TANK.  HOSE END SLIPPED OUT OF UNLOADER'S HAND AND DROPPED, SPILLING 1 1/2 GALLON ON THE GROUND.  OIL DRY WAS SPREAD AND DIRT AND OIL DRY WAS PICKED UP AND DISPOSED OF BY CONSIGNEE'S PERSONNEL.

AND ARRIVED AT CHICAGO AT 12:20 P.M. wE RENTED A CAR AND DROVE TO CHAMPAIGN, IL., AND ARRIVED AND THE CHAMPAIGN RAIL YARD AT 7:00 A.M. THE GASKET ON THE VAPOR LOADING VALVE WAS REPLACED WITH A NEW GASKET AND THE BLIND FLANGE WAS BOLTED DOWN SQUARELY AND FIRMLY AND EASILY STOPPING THE LEAK.  GATX-62148 WAS SECURED BY 8:30 AM 5/28/99.

A DOCK MAN WAS UNLOADING BIR TRAILER S30756 TO FIND A SPILL OF DRUMS SEVENTY FIVE PERCENT INSIDE THE TRAILER.  AT THE TIME OF DISCOVERY THE DOCK MAN REPORTED THE SPILL TO ME.  AT THIS TIME, I IMMEDIATELY LOOKED AT THE FREIGHT BILL TO FIND THE PRODUCT SPILLED TO BE CORROSIVE AND SUBSIDIARY PERSON.  FROM THIS POINT I TOOK A PICTURE OF THE DAMAGE CLOSED THE TRAILER DOOR AND MOVED THE TRAILER AWAY FROM THE DOCK.  I THEN CALLED CHEMTREC AND EDDIE YANCE IN DOTHAN, AL., TO REPORT THE SPILL.  EDDIE TOLD ME TO CALL GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES TO THE MORNING TO HANDLE DECONTAMINATION. ACTION TAKEN TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS WAS FOLLOWED BY TAKING PICTURES OF THE LOAD THAT CAUSED THE DAMAGE AND SENDING THEM BACK TO THE ORIGIN TERMINAL FOR FURTHER TRAINING.

ON MAY 25,1999, AT APPROXIMATELY 1010 HOURS, A RAILROAD TANK CAR, TANK CAR NUMBER ECUX 405269, LOADED WITH CHLOROTOLUENES, WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM THE DOME LID WHILE BEING SWITCHED AT KCS' BATON ROUGE, LOUISIANA RAIL YARD. THE TANK CAR WAS IMMEDIATELY ISOLATED TO PREVENT FURTHER MOVEMENT AND POSSIBLE LEAKAGE FROM THE DEFECTIVE DOME LID SEAL. THE SHIPPER (RESPONSIBLE PARTY) WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED OF THEIR DEFECTIVE TANK CAR. THE TRANSPORTER MADE IMMEDIATE NOTIFICATION TO THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE (REPORT #992845) AND TO THE LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY. THE SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES RESPONDED TO THE SITE AND MADE NECESSARY REPAIRS, CORRECTING THE LEAK AT 1242 HOURS THAT SAME DAY.

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE LEAKAGE/DAMAGE OCCURRED.  APPARENTLY THE PACKAGE WAS DROPPED IN HANDLING RUPTURING THE UNIT AND ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION.

WHILE ATTEMPTING TO TRANSFER THE PRODUCT FROM THE DRUM TO THE STORAGE TANK, THE TRANSFER PUMP FAILED TO PRIME AND WAS UNABLE TO TRANSFER. SOME LIQUID MADE ITS WAY INTO THE PUMP'S INLET HOSE, BUT WHEN THIS HOSE WAS DISCONNECTED FROM THE PUMP, A SMALL QUANTITY OF ACID SPILLED OUT AND SPATTERED. A FEW DROPS OF LIQUID HIT TWO GREAT WESTERN CHEMICAL CO. EMPLOYEES. THE EMPLOYEES WERE TREATED IMMEDIATELY, AND THE RELEASE WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODIUM BICARBONTE, AND AT THE DIRECTION OF THE CUSTOMER, RINSED INTO CONTAINMENT. A NEW, MORE POWERFUL TRANSFER PUMP WILL BE OBTAINED TO PREVENT REOCCURENCE.

DRIVER MADE A MATH ERROR WHEN CHECKING TO MAKE SURE THAT THE LOAD WOULD FIT. THE MISCALCULATION RESULTED IN THE SPILL. THE DRIVER WAS GIVEN A CALCULATOR AND WAS INSTRUCTED TO VERIFY ALL FIGURES BEFORE UNLOADING. OUR ENVIRONMENTAL CONSULTANTS RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT. ALL CONTAMINATED SOILS WITHIN THE DIKE WERE REMOVED AND DISPOSED OF IN AN APPROVED MANNER. NEW SOILS WERE THEN PLACED WITHIN THE DIKED AREA.

column168: DESCRIPTION OF THE INCIDENT:  ON 5/25/99, A TRUCK SHIPMENT OF INTER MODAL CONTAINERS ARRIVED AT THE GENERAL MATERIALS TERMINAL AT CONWAY, PA., FROM THE B&W DECOMMISIONING SITE TO BE TRANSFER TO RAIL FOR CONVEYANCE TO PASCO, WA.  GENERAL MATERIALS WAS UNABLE TO LIFT CONTAINER MHFU 001003 DUE TO THE CONFIGURATION OF THEIR NEWLY OBTAINED SPREADER DEVICE.  THE OPERATOR DECIDED TO WAIT AND LOAD MHFU 001003 LAST UTILIZING ALTERNATE AUTHORIZED RIGGING METHODS. MHFU 003001 WAS BLOCKING THE OTHER CONTAINERS TO BE LOADED AND WAS ATTEMPTED TO "SHOVED" OUT THE WAY UTILIZING A BUCKET LOADER.  THE OPERATOR DAMAGED MHFU 003001 IN ATTEMPTING TO MOVE THE CONTAINER BY THE CORNER WITH THE BUCKET LOADER.  GENERAL MATERIALS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED MHF-LS VIA TELEPHONE THAT THEY HAD DAMAGED A CONTAINER. GENERAL MATERIALS REPORTED A 6-8 INCH GOUGE WAS PUT INTO THE CONTAINER BY THE CORNER OF THE BUCKET.  GENERAL MATERIALS STOP MOVEMENT OF THE CONTAINER, ROPED OFF THE AREA AROUND THE CONTAINER, AND WITNESSED NO MATERIAL WAS COMING FROM THE GOUGE.  MHF-LS INSTRUCTED GENERAL MATERIALS TO STOP LOADING AND TO WAIT UNTIL REPRESENTATIVES FROM MHF-LS AND B&W COULD SURVEY THE INCIDENT.  b&W HEALTH PHYSICS PERSONNEL AT THE INCIDENT SURVEY THE GOUGE AND THE BUCKET AND DETERMINED THAT THE CONTAINER HAD BEEN DAMAGED.  A DECISION WAS MADE TO PATCH THE GOUGE WITH DEVCON SEALANT AND A PLATE OF METAL UTILIZING SELF-TAPPING SCREWS AND PAINT THE REPAIRED AREA. THE AREA WAS RESURVEY BY B&W PERSONNEL WHICH RESULT IN NEGATIVE RESULTS.  IMMEDIATE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS:  PERSONNEL OF GENERAL MATERIALS STOP OPERATIONS AND ROPED OFF AREA.  QUALIFIED B&W PERSONNEL SURVEYED THE AREA.  A "STRONG-TIGHT" PATCH WAS APPLIED TO ALLOW CONTAINER TO BE SHIPPED.  ROOT CAUSE:  THE INCIDENT OCCURRED AS A RESULT OF ATTEMPTING TO RELOCATE A CONTAINER WITH A FRONT END BUCKET LOADER.  A GENERAL MATERIALS OPERATOR ATTEMPTED TO POSITION THE CONTAINER BY APPLYING THE BUCKET OF THE LOADER AGAINST THE CONER POST OF THE CONTAINER AND FORCE THE CONTAINER FORWARD.  THE BUCKET SLIPPED OFF THE CORNER POST AND IMPELLED THE FRONT OF THE LOWER LEFT-HAND CORNER OF THE CONTAINER CREATING A 6 TO 8 INCH GOUGE INTO THE CONTAINER.  THE ROOT CAUSE IS OPERATOR ERROR, WHICH LED TO IMPROPER SELECTION OF EQUIPMENT TO RELOCATE THE CONTAINER.  ACTIONS TO PREVENT RECURRENCE:  ON 5/25/99 MHF-LS PERSONNEL INTERVIEWED AND REVIEWED THE INCIDENT WITH GENERAL MATERIALS PERSONNEL.  ON 5/25/99 A POLICY LETTER WAS PRESENT TO GENERAL MATERIALS PERSONNEL ON HANDLING COMMUNICATED TO GENERAL MATERIALS BY MHF-LS.  LOADING AND HANDLING OF THE CONTAINERS WAS WITNESS TO VERIFY IMPLEMENTATION OF THE POLICIES.  THE NEXT SHIPMENT WILL ALSO BE WITNESS BY MHF-LS PERSONNEL TO ASSURE IMPLEMENTATION OF THE POLICIES.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE TRAVELING ON HIGHWAY 36, WESTBOUND, IN MILTON, KENTUCKY,  THE DRIVER SWERVED AS TO AVOID AN ONCOMING VEHICLE, APPARENTLY CAUSING THE TRACTOR/TRAILER UNIT TO ROLL-OVER ONTO THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD.  SIX, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUMS WERE DAMAGED AS A RESULT OF THE VEHICULAR ACCIDENT. APPROXIMATELY FIFTY-SIX GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND AFFECTED SOME SOIL.  THE MILTON FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE KENTUCKY STATE POLICE RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  DOW CORNING CORPORATION'S CHEMICAL RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED AND APPLIED SAND TO THE AFFECTED AREA. DOW CORNING OFFLOADED THE DAMAGED FREIGHT AND OVERPACKED THE LEAKING DRUMS. THE OVERPACK DRUMS WERE TRANSPORTED TO DOW CORNING CORPORATION'S  FACILITY IN CARROLLTON, KENTUCKY FOR DISPOSAL.  AST INDUSTRIAL & ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES OF LOUISVILLE, KENTUCKY RESPONDED TO PERFORM THE REMAINDER OF THE CLEANUP,   WHICH INVOLVED THE REMOVAL OF SAND AND SOIL FROM THE IMPACTED AREA.  THE SAND AND SOIL WERE PLACED INTO FOUR ROLL-OFF BOXES WHICH WERE TRANSPORTED TO OUTER LOOP RDG OF LOUISVILLE, KENTUCKY FOR DISPOSAL. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.  ALL STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.

OUR DRIVER WAS GOING DOWN AN EXTREMELY LONG AND HILLY ROAD WHEN HE EXPERIENCED BRAKE FADE.  SUBSEQUENTLY HE LOST CONTROL OF HIS UNIT AND RAN OFF THE ROAD NEAR A REST STOP AT THE END OF THE HILL AND THE LOAD OF WASTE IN A BIN MOUNTED ON A TRAILER WAS SPILLED.  THE ACCIDENT WAS THOROUGHLY INVESTIGATED BY OUR COMPANY AND THE CALIFORNIA HIGHWAY PATROL ACCIDENT INVESTIGATION TEAM.  NO MECHANICAL DEFECTS WERE FOUND BY EITHER OUR MECHANICS OR THE CALIFORNIA HIGHWAY PATROL.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT IT WAS SIMPLY A MATTER OF DRIVER ERROR.  AS A RESULT OF OUR INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THIS ROUTE, WHICH WAS ASSIGNED TO THIS DRIVER, PRESENTED TOO MUCH OF A HAZARD AND AS SUCH WE HAVE NEVER ROUTED ANY OF OUR LOADS THROUGH HIGHWAY 190 AGAIN AND WILL NOT DO SO IN THE FUTURE.

column168: ONE 5/6/99 A SPILL WAS REPORTED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177.  THE LOCATION OF THE SPILL WAS IN OUR "C" BUILDING SORT FACILITY.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN, JEFF KIDDER RESPONDED, UPON ARRIVAL JEFF DONNED HIS PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND BEGAN HIS INVESTIGATION.  HE FOUND ONE FIBERBOARD BOX WITH SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER BOX.  THE OUTER BOX WAS MARKED AS FOLLOWS:  THE TOP OF THE BOX HAD AN LIBRA AIRWAY BILL LABEL, SIDE ONE OF THE BOX: MADE IN U.S.A., BY PRECISIONAIRE INC., PRECISIONAIRE, 20 X20 X1, CATALOG #F12020 & 1, ONE DOZEN (12), SPUN GLASS, PRECISIONAIRE HEAVY DUTY, DISPOSABLE PANEL AIRE FILTERS. SIDE 3, IS THE SAME AS SIDE 1.  SIDE 2 IS THE SAME AS SIDE 1.  SIDE 4 IS THE SAME AS SIDE 1.  THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX HAD THE FOLLOWING MARKINGS, GEORGIA PACIFIC, LAKE PLACID.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CERTIFICATIONS TO INDICATE THIS SHIPMENT TO CONTAIN REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER BOX THE FOLLOWING WAS FOUND: 63 METAL RECEPTACLES AT ONE PINT EACH.  THE CLOSURES WERE SCREW TYPE AND HAD NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE WHICH RESULTED IN LOOSE CLOSURES.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS ALSO LOADED AGAINST ORIENTATION.  THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY 8 OUNCES OF DIESEL FUEL THAT LEAKED FORM ONE OF THE PINT CONTAINERS.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS ALSO LOADED AGAINST ORIENTATION.  THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY 6 OUNCES OF DIESEL FUEL THAT LEAKED FROM ONE OF THE PINT CONTAINERS.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT PACKED WITH ANY ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM DUE TO THE ODOR AND SPILL.  THIS SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD FOR FAA INVESTIGATION.

ON MAY 5, 1999, THE UNLOAD CREW DISCOVERED A WET PACKAGE LOCATED IN BELLY THREE OF FLIGHT 372(TAIL 851AX).  THEY IMMEDIATELY EVACUATED AREA AND CONTACTED SUPERVISOR GARY COOK.  HE IDENTIFIED THE PACKAGE AS HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  GARY WITH PROPER TRAINING, REMOVED THE PACKAGE FROM THE BELLY AND ISOLATED THE PACKAGE.  GARY AND RAJ (AIRCRAFT MECHANIC) INSPECTED THE BELLY OF PLANE AND FOUND NO RESIDUE FROM HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.   DRY SIDE WAS TOUCHING PLANE BELLY SURFACE.  THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED AS PER THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE BOOK.  IT WILL BE PUT IN A RECOVERY CAN AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER FOR DISPOSAL.

ALL WORK ON THIS TRAILER WAS STOPPED AT THAT TIME.  FOS M HURT CONTACTED THE CHEM-TREK EMERGENCY PHONE NUMBER FOR ASSISTANCE ON THE PROPER HANDLING AND CLEANUP OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. column168: AT APPROX 1900 ON 5/3/99, FOS J. HIRST BECAME AWARE OF A H/M SPILL. AFTER INVESTIGATION, SHE CONTACTED SCM RON STROHLEY & SAFETY SUPERVISOR BILL MCCURRY.  ATTEMPTS WERE MADE TO CALL THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE NUMBER AND RECEIVED NO ANSWER.  SHIPPER HAS FINALLY CONTACTED AT 0630.  THEY SENT AN EMPLOYEE TO REPLACE A DEFECTIVE VALVE.  SHIPPER FELT VERY LITTLE PRODUCT WAS LOST AND SHIPPER IS TAKING THE CYLINDER BACK FOR INSPECTION.

FILE AB2099 F&D, SHIPPER: RINECO, AWB #LIT 6883608046 OKC.  THIS WAS AN UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPMENT.  ON 5/7/99 AN ODOR WAS REPORTED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OH 46177. THE LOCATION OF THE ODOR WAS ON AIRCRAFT, FLYT 233, TAIL # N931AX, TOPSIDE OF THE AIRCRAFT AT GATE A-44.  PART-TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS CHARLES JONES AND TIM HINES RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL DISCOVERED A STRONG ODOR AND REQUESTED ADDITIONAL ASSISTANCE.  AFTER THE RESPONSE TEAMS ARRIVED AND DONNED THEIR PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, THEY BEGAN THEIR INSPECTION.  UPON LOCATION OF THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE CONTAINING THE ODOR, THE DECISION WAS MADE TO REMOVE THIS OFF THE AIRCRAFT TO A SECURE AREA.  THE INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER FOUND THE FOLLOWING: 1 FIBERBOARD BOX CONTAINING A 1 GALLON METAL RECEPTACLE CONTAINING AN 18 OUNCE GLASS RECEPTACLE.  THE INSPECTION FOUND THE GLASS RECEPTACLE TO ONLY RESIDUE LEFT IN THE RECEPTACLE. THE INSPECTION FOUND THE FIBERBOARD BOX TO HAVE ABSORBED MOST OF THE LIQUID AND APPROXIMATELY 1 OUNCE OF A ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE, LIQUID NOS TO HAVE LEAKED OUT OF THE PACKAGE,  THE LEAK WAS DUE TO A LOOSE CLOSURE.  THE FOLLOWING IS A RECAP OF THE MARKINGS AND LABELING OF THE SHIPMENT: THE INNER GLASS RECEPTACLE HAD NO DOCUMENTATION OF MARKINGS OR LABELING.  THE METAL RECEPTACLE CONTAINING THE GLASS RECEPTACLE HAD NO DOCUMENTATION OF ANY MARKINGS OR LABELS.  THE FIBERBOARD BOX CONTAINING THE METAL AND GLASS RECEPTACLE HAD THE FOLLOWING MARKINGS AND LABELS: THE TOP PF THE BOX HAD NOTHING. 2 SIDES OF THE BOX HAD PRE-PRINTED ORIENTATION ARROWS, 1 SIDE OF THE BOX HAD UN 4GV/X1.2/S/98/USA+AA/630/APSS ACCEPTABLE FOR AIR SHIPMENT, 1 SIDE OF THE BOX HAD RCI 260312, ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE, LIQUID NOS (FUEL) UN 3082 AND A CLASS 9 LABEL. THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX HAD THE FOLLOWING: GRIEF BROS CORP., WASHINGTON, PA, WT 100LBS.  ALSO FOUND ON THE BOX WAS THE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS, A DOT EXEMPTION DOT E-9188, A STURDESSEEAL HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ASSEMBLY INSTRUCTIONS. THIS SHIPMENT WAS FOUND WRAPPED IN PLAIN WHITE PACKING PAPER WITH NO MARKINGS OR LABELS TO INDICATE THIS SHIPMENT TO CONTAIN A REGULATED MATERIAL.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM OUR TO ODOR AND IS BEING HELD FOR FAA INVESTIGATION.

column168: FILE AB 1999 FHWA, SHIPPER: WILLAMETTE INDUSTRIES, AWB #FSM 6180127082 JLN.  THIS IS A 5800.1 REPORT ONLY.  ON 5/8/99 AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 46177, THE LOCATION OF THE SPILL WAS IN OUR C BUILDING SORTING FACILITY.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN PAUL SCHMIDT RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL PAUL WAS GIVEN A BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX TO CHECK OUT.  UPON OPENING THE BOX AN ODOR WAS NOTICED AND A LABEL OF A 8.1.  THE BOX WAS QUICKLY CLOSED AND BAGGED AND RETURN TO THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SORT AREA FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE OUTER PACKAGE THE FOLLOWING WAS FOUND: THE TOP OF THE BOX WAS BLANK, SIDE 1 OF THE BOX HAD A REGULAR AIRWAY BILL, SIDE 2 OF THE BOX WAS BLANK, SIDE 3 OF THE BOX WAS BLANK, SIDE 4 OF THE BOX HAD THIS END UP AND AN ORIENTATION ARROW DRAWN ON THE BOX.  THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX WAS ALSO BLANK.  THERE WERE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER BOX.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS THE FOLLOWING: 2x1 GALLON METAL RECEPTACLES THAT WERE FOUND TO HAVE A LOOSE CLOSURE DUE TO NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THIS CLOSURE.  1 RECEPTACLE LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 4 OUNCES OF (TOXIC LIQUIDS, ORGANIC, NOS (DICHLOROMETHANE), UN2810.  THE INNER RECEPTACLE WAS MARKED AND LABELED AS A STOW AWAY FROM FOOD STUFF.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM DUE TO LEAKAGE AND ODOR AND WE ARE AWAITING FOR THE PROPER SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS TO FORWARD THIS SHIPMENT.  THIS WAS BELIEVED TO HAVE COME INTO LLN BY TRUCK.  PHOTOS WERE TAKEN OF THIS SHIPMENT TO FORWARD WITH THIS REPORT.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THE OUTER PACKAGE TO INDICATE THIS TO CONTAIN A REGULATED MATERIAL.

THE BOX WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING.  THE BOX WAS OPENED TO REVEAL A ONE-GALLON METAL DRUM THAT WAS LEAKING.  IN ADDITION, THERE WAS A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET (MSDS).  THE MSDS REVEALED THE FLASH POINT TO BE 35 DEGREE F.  THE BOX WAS PLACED IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.  THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED IN RDU.  HOWEVER, DENISE CROUSE WAS UNAVAILABLE, SO I CALLED LYNN LEONARD WITH THE ATL CASFO.  THE FREIGHT IS BEING HELD PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION.
PACKAGE WAS IN HAZ MAT, SOMEONE RESPONDED.  PUT 3 GALLON JUGS IN SALVAGE DRUM.  RTS'ED.  PUT WASTE IN DMP BAG AND PROCESSED THRU THE DMP PROGRAM.

DOCK WORKER WAS LOADING ANOTHER SHIPMENT ON TRAILER AND HIT THE CTN WITH TOW MOTOR CAUSING INNER PLASTIC JUG TO BURST.  CONTENTS RAN OUT IN TRAILER.  EMERGENCY NUMBER WAS NOTIFIED AND MSDS SECURED FROM SHIPPER.  ENVIRONMENTAL PRODUCTS AND SERVICES WAS CALLED TO CLEAN UP SPILL AND TO NEUTRALIZE OTHER FRT THAT HAS BEEN WET BY SOLUTION. DAMAGED MDSE AND CLEANUP DEBRIS WILL BE DISPOSED OF BY ENVIRONMENTAL PRODUCTS AND SERVICES IN ACCORDANCE WITH ALL LAWS.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0600 HRS LOCAL CREW CHIEF BILL GANDY INFORMED ME THAT HERE WAS SOME LIQUID LEAKING FROM A BAG ON A BAGGAGE CART. BILL BROUGHT THE BAG TO THE OFFICE AND I IMMEDIATELY WENT TO GATE 35 AND PAGED THE PSGR TO VERIFY THE CONTENTS.  MRS. GOLDEN SAID THAT HER HUSBAND PACKED THE BAG AND SHE WAS NOT SURE WHAT WAS LEAKING FROM IT.  THE BAG WAS A MED SIZE BLACK NYLON DUFFLE W/SIDE POCKETS. INSIDE ONE OF THE POCKETS WAS A 320% PLASTIC SPRAY BOTTLE WITH THE SPRAYER BROKEN OFF LABELED - GREEN LIGHT FUNG-AWAY LAWN SPRAY.  MOST OF THE LIQUID WAS STILL INSIDE THE BAG.  FSC ROBT FRANKLIN AND I ABSORBED THE LIQUID FROM THE BAG INTO A PLASTIC BAG USING PAPER TOWELS AND CLEANED THE POCKET THOROUGHLY.  I INFORMED THE PSGR THAT I WOULD NOT ALLOW THE BAG TO BE LOADED ON AN AA AIRCRAFT BECAUSE I NEEDED MORE INFORMATION TO DETERMINE IF THE LIQUID WAS NON-HAZARDOUS.  SHE ASKED ME TO CALL HER HUSBAND AT THE MARRIOTT HOTEL AND HAVE HIM PICKUP THE BAG.  I CONTACTED THE LOCAL AIRPORT POLICE TO MAKE A REPORT AND TO VERIFY OTHER CONTENTS IN THE BAG THAT MAY CONTAIN CHEMICALS.

column168: SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING INBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DISCREPANCY WAS DISCOVERED.  THE PACKAGE WAS BEING HANDLED WHEN HANDLING PERSONNEL NOTICED LEAKAGE AND A PAINT THINNER LIKE ODOR COMING FROM THE PACKAGE.  THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED AND OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL 16 ONE QUART METAL CANS OF SOME TYPE OF FURNITURE STAIN.  APPARENTLY THE LID SEAL ON ONE OF THE CANS FAILED ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL.  MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS OBTAINED FROM THE SHIPPER.  INFORMATION ON THE DOCUMENT INDICATED THAT THE MATERIAL EXHIBITED FLASPOINTS TO BE LOW ENOUGH GOT THEM TO BE CONSIDERED AS REGULATED FLAMMABLE PAINT RELATED MATERIAL.  THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKINGS OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE SURFACE OF THE PACKAGE.  A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS WAS NOT IN EVIDENCE WITH THIS SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE FAA FOR INVESTIGATION.  PHONE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO SPECIAL AGENT ALEX EVANS/FAA/BNA/CAFSO AT 12:15 N (CST) ON 5/18/99.

THIS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED TO BE EXHIBITING AN ODOR AND WAS HELD AT THE DESTINATION STATION.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS IT CONTAINED A FUEL CONTROL UNIT WHICH APPEARED TO BE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS, NAMELY "FUEL AVIATION TURBINE ENGINE".  FAA AGENT TONY NGUYEN WAS NOTIFIED.  FEDEX WILL HOLD THE SHIPMENT PENDING HIS INVESTIGATION.

column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING AN INBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DAMAGE/LEAKAGE OCCURRED.  THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING SORTED WHEN HANDLING PERSONNEL NOTICED WHAT APPEARED TO BE BLOOD RELEASING FROM THE PACKAGE.  THE PACKAGE WAS IMMEDIATELY ISOLATED, OPENED, AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL SEVERAL VIALS OF BLOOD THAT HAD BEEN BROKEN IN HANDLING.  PRIOR TO CONTACT WITH THE SHIPPER THIS WAS THOUGHT TO BE THE INFECTIOUS COMPONENT OF THE SHIPMENT.  HOWEVER AFTER CONTACT WITH THE SHIPPER HAD BEEN MADE IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE INFECTIOUS COMPONENT OF THE SHIPMENT HAD REMAINED INTACT IN THE PACKAGE AND WAS NOT DAMAGED.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION.  BECAUSE OF THE RELEASE OF BLOOD FROM THE SHIPMENT A REPORT WAS MADE BY TELEPHONE TO SPECIAL AGENT DON STIGER/FAA/PDX/CAFSO AS WELL AS TO THE CDC IN ATLANTA, GA IN COMPLIANCE WITH 49 CFR 171.15  (A) (3).

SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DISCREPANCY WAS DISCOVERED.  THE PACKAGE WAS BEING HANDLED WHEN HANDLING PERSONNEL NOTICED LEAKAGE AND A GASOLINE LIKE ODOR COMING FROM THE TWO HARD PLASTIC COOLERS.  THE PACKAGES WERE ISOLATED OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL 15 GLASS BOTTLES. SIX OF THE BOTTLES BETWEEN THE TWO COOLERS HAD APPARENTLY BEEN BROKEN IN TRANSIT. THERE WAS NO ABSORBENT MATERIAL IN EITHER OF THE COOLERS.  THE MATERIAL APPEARED TO BE WATER SAMPLES THAT WERE BEING SENT TO BE TESTED FOR GASOLINE CONTAMINATION.  THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKINGS OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE SURFACE OF THE PACKAGE.  A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS FOODS WAS NOT IN EVIDENCE WITH THIS SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE FAA FOR INVESTIGATION.  PHONE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO SPECIAL AGENT JOE BALLAS/FAA/EWR/CAFSO AT 13:30 ON 5/13/99.

ON 5/10/99 WHILE CHECKING THE LOADING I DISCOVERED A PACKAGE THAT WAS LEAKING A FLUID.  WHEN I DISCOVERED THE PLACARD, I IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE STATION MANAGER AND CLEANED UP THE AREA.  THE BOX WAS DOUBLE-WRAPPED AND QUICK DRY APPLIED ON THE FLOOR.  THE PACKAGE WAS REMOVED FROM THE AREA AND ALDRICH CHEMICAL WAS CONTACTED.  EMAIL TO ILN HAZMAT (JOHN HANDY) WAS ALSO SENT.  ALDRICH SEND AND X-RAY CONTAINER TO RLE WHICH ARRIVED ON 5/12/99.  PKG WA SHIPPED TO ROU ON 5/12/99.

ON 5/8/99 A SPILL WAS REPORTED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE Wilmington, OHIO 45177. THE LOCATION OF THE SPILL WAS IN OUR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SORT FACILITY. PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS, MATTHEW GROSVENOR AND JEFF KIDDER RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL THEY DONNED THEIR PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION. THEY FOUND OUR FIBERBOARD BOX LEAKING AND EMITTING AN ODOR. THE OUTER BOX WAS MARKED AS FOLLOWS: THE TOP OF THE BOX HAD A PRE-PRINTED PUROLATOR MARKING, AN AIRWAY BILL THAT COULD NOT BE REMOVED FROM THE BOX TO COPY, SIDE 1 HAD A LABEL THAT READ "LTD QTY", PROPYLENE TETRAMER, CLASS 3, UN2850, PG III, ALSO ATTACHED WAS A FLAMMABLE LIQUID LABEL. THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX WAS MARKED, ICC, MISSISSAUGA, ONTARIO, 55 LBS GROSS, SIDE 2 HAD ORIENTATION ARROWS, A PRE-PRINTED IC MARKING, THE FOLLOWING STATEMENT; FOR LIQUIDS WHEN INNER RECEPTACLES MEETS THE INTERNAL PRESSURE TESTING REQUIREMENTS., SPECIFICATION MARKINGS: UN 4GV/X4.1/S/97 CAN/ICC 2-83, AIR APPROVED. THE ATTACHMENTS WERE: THE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS AND A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET. THERE WERE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER BOX. UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER PACKAGE THE FOLLOWING WAS FOUND: ONE METAL GALLON RECEPTACLE PACKED IN VERMICULITE. THE INSPECTION FOUND THE BOTTOM WELD SEAM TO HAVE FAILED AND LEAK APPROXIMATELY 10 OUNCES. THE ONLY REASON FOUND FOR THE LEAKAGE WAS FAILURE OF THE WELD SEAM. THIS SHIPMENT WAS MARKED, LABELED AND THE PROPER HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CERTIFICATIONS DID ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT. THE SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND WAS FORWARDED ONTO THE DESTINATION.

THE MORNING OF 5/25/99, DURING OUR AM SORT OPERATIONS, I (JAMES ASHBY) WAS INFORMED BY A DRIVER, JOHN HOLLINS, THAT A PACKAGE WAS LEAKING BEHIND HIS TRUCK I OBTAINED THE PACKING LIST AND MARKINGS FROM THE BOX, NOTING A CLEAR LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX, I IDENTIFIED THE SUBSTANCE TO BE HAZARDOUS CLEARED THE AREA OF PERSONNEL AND SECURED THE SPILL WITH OIL DRY, ROPED OFF THE AREA TO PREVENT ACCESS, CONTACTED OUR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SUPPORT GROUP AND ADVISED THEM OF THE SPILL AND CONTENTS. WAS INFORMED TO MAINTAIN VENTILATION AND DISTANCE FROM AREA, I INFORMED THE ORIGINATING STATION AND SHIPPER OF THE SPILL AND AWAITED FOR A SPILL RESPONSE TEAM TO ARRIVE FOR CLEAN UP AND DISPOSAL I SUPERVISED THE AREA TO PREVENT ACCESS UNTIL THE TEAM ARRIVED AT 1030, THEY PROCEEDED TO ISOLATE AND CLEAN THE SPILL AREA AND CONTAIN WASTE PRODUCTS IN DRUM. THE CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETED AT 1100.

THE ASHLAND TRUCK DRIVER, DAVID KUSH, ARRIVED AT MCGILL MANUFACTURING BACKED INTO UNLOADING DOCK, OPENED THE TRAILER DOORS AND ENTERED THE TRAILER WITH EMPTY DRUM. AS HE ENTERED THE TRAILER HE NOTICED THE DRUM CART THAT HAD PREVIOUSLY BEEN SECURED TO THE SIDE OF THE TRIALER  WAS ON THE FLOOR NEXT TO THE SULFURIC DRUM. HE NOTICED THE TIE DOWN STRAP HAD BROKEN. HE THEN SAW SULFURIC ACID RUNNING ON THE TRAILER FLOOR TOWARD THE BACK OF THE TRAILER. HE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED A MCGILL EMPLOYEE WHO PLACED A BARRIER IN THE BACK OF THE TRAILER  TO CONTAIN THE SPILL. THE  MONTICELLO FIRE DEPT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAMWAS CALLED,ARRIVED AND NEUTRALIZED THE SULFURIC ACID IN THE TRAILER WITH SODA ASH LIMESTONE. IDEM SPILL LINE WAS ALSO NOTIFIED. ASHLAND CALLED IN MIDWEST MATERIAL SERVICES TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL. MIDWEST PIUGGED THE HOLE IN THE DRUM THAT HAD BEEN CAUSED BY THE DRUM CART. THE DRUM ALONG WITH APPROXIMATELY 27 GALLONS REMAINING IN THE DRUM WAS PLACED IN AN OVERPACK  DRUM. MIDWEST CLEANED UP THE SODA ASH, LIME, FLOOR SWEEP,AND NEUTRALIZED SULFURIC ACID AND PUT IT IN THREE 55 GALLON DRUMS. column168: DEAN C COOPER MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY ROBERT WETZEL, GENERAL MANAGER TRANSLOADING ENVIRONMENTAL REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR AT THE COLTON YARD.  MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED DENNIS JOHNSON MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAGETY TUCSON ARIZONA AND WAS ADVISED THE ABOVE TANK CAR WAS IN THE COLTON RECEIVING YARD AND FOUND LEAKING FROM THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS OBSERVED LEAKING BY MECHANICAL DEPT FORCES WHILE PERFORMING NORMAL CAR INSPECTIONS.  SINCE THE TANK CAR WAS BURIED IN THE MIDDLE OF THE RECEIVING YARD TRACK #205, ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH THE YARDMASTER TO SEPARATE RECEIVING YARD TRACK #206 IN ORDER TO ACCESS THE AREA.  MANAGER COOPER ARRIVED ON SCENE AND MET WITH SAN BERNARDINO COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT BATTALION CHIEF SCHROEDER, SAN BERNARDINO COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZMAT SPECIALIST SNIDER AND SAN BERNARDINO COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DIVISION SPECIALIST BECKHAM/ MITCH DUGGER, ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEER WAS ALSO ON SCENE TO PROVIDE ASSISTANCE.  ONCE THE 206 TRACK WAS CLEARED FOR OBSERVATION IT WAS NOTED THE TANK CAR HAD A PRODUCT TRAIL DOWN THE SIDE OF THE CAR AND LIQUID WAS STEADILY DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK CAR.  A CLOSER INSPECTION NOTED THE PRODUCT BEING EMITTED FROM THE PROTECTIVE COVER THAT HOUSES THE LIQUID AND AIR VALVES.  THE TANK WAS ALSO INSPECTED FOR TEMPERATURE LEVELS AT ALL FOUR OF THE BOULSTER OPENINGS IN AN EFFORT TO DETERMINE IF THE PRODUCT WAS HEATING UP.  THE DRIPPING LIQUID WAS ALSO MONITORED FOR TEMPERATURE LEVELS AND FOUND TO BE WITHIN NORMAL RANGE. AFTER THE INITIAL ASSESSMENT WAS MADE, A 3 MAN TEAM C ONSISTING OF MANAGER COOPER SPECIALIST SNIDER AND SPECIALIST BECKHAM RE-ENTERED THE AREA AND CLIMBED THE TANK CAR.  UPON OPENING THE PROTECTIVE VALVE COVER A CLEAR PRODUCT TRAIL WAS NOTED COMING FROM THE LIQUID LINE VALVE.  THE LIQUID LINE BALL VALVE WAS IN THE CLOSED POSITION AND THE PIPE PLUG WAS TIGHT, HOWEVER, PRODUCT WAS STILL BEING EMITTED FROM THE LIQUID LINE.  THE AIR LINE PIPE PLUG WAS REMOVED AND THE BALL VALVE CRACKED IN ORDER TO RELIEVE THE INTERNAL PRESSURE OF THE TANK CAR.  THE AIR LINE VENTED FOR 3-4 MINUTES BEFORE THE PRESURE BECAME NEUTRAL, INDICATING THE CAR HAD LESS THAT 5 PSI.  ONCE THE PRESSURE WAS RELIEVED IN THE TANK CAR THE PRODUCT CEASED DISCHARGING THROUGH THE LIQUID LINE.  THE LIQUID LINE PIPE PLUG WAS REMOVED AND THE BALL VALVE INSPECTED.  THE BALL VALVE DID NOT APPEAR TO BE DAMAGED, AND IT IS NOT KNOWN IF THE BALL WAS SCARRED OR THE SEAT WAS DEFECTIVE.  THE PIPE PLUG WAS NOTED TO HAVE SEVERAL GOUGES AT THE THREADS AND SINCE THE PLUG HAD NO TAPE ON THE THREADS, ONCE THE PRODUCT BY PASSED THE BALL VALVE, IT WAS ALSO ABLE TO BYPASS THE PLUG, EVEN THOUGH IT WAS TIGHT.  TEFLON TAPE WAS APPLIED TO THE PIPE PLUG AND THE PLUG WAS PLACED BACK ONTO THE LIQUID LINE.  AS THE CAR WAS NO LONGER LEAKING PRODUCT AND THE SOURCE HAD BEEN SECURED THE INCIDENT WAS BROUGHT TO A CLOSE. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO HOLD THE CAR AT THE ONE SPOT RIP TRAC

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: BILL FULLER WAS NORTH BOUND ON HIGHWAY 67 ON THE SOUTH SIDE OF LYONS, IN. AT APPROXIMATELY 5:58 AM.  AS HE SLOWED TO ROUND A CURVE THE BACK AMMONIA TANK THAT HE WAS PULLING OVERTURNED.  WHEN IT DID IT ENTERED THE ONCOMING LANE AND STRUCK THE SIDE OF AN ONCOMING CAR.  THE IMPACT BROKE THE TANK OFF ITS RUNNING GEAR AND CAUSED THE TANK TO ROLL ALL THE WAY OVER.  THIS BROKE THE SAFETY GAUGE AND BROKE A POP-OFF VALVE CAUSING AMMONIA TO RELEASE INTO THE ATMOSPHERE.  THE LYONS FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND BEGAN TO PUT A WATER FOG ON THE AMMONIA PLUME.  THIS WAS DONE UNTIL THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE TANK (850 GALLONS) HAD DISPERSED INTO THE ATMOSPHERE.  THE DRIVER OF THE CAR THAT WAS STRUCK BY THE TANK WAS HOSPITALIZED AND ONE OTHER PERSON THAT SMELLED THE AMMONIA WAS HOSPITALIZED FOR 1 HOUR.  8 OTHER PEOPLE WERE EVACUATED FROM THEIR HOMES FOR A PERIOD OF TIME AND THE LOCAL SCHOOL PRACTICED "SHELTER IN PLACE" DURING THE INCIDENT. THE AMMONIA BURNED BUSHES AT THE NEIGHBORING PARK AND THEY WERE REPLACED. THE WATER FROM THE WATER FOG WAS RECOVERED AND TAKEN TO THE SWITZ CITY FACILITY WERE IT WAS APPLIED TO CROPLAND AT AGRONOMIC RATES.  IF YOU HAVE FURTHER QUESTIONS ABOUT THIS INCIDENT PLEASE DO NOT HESITATE TO CONTACT ME AT 217-472-7015.  THANK YOU FOR YOUR COOPERATION CONCERNING THIS MATTER.
